  "prompt": "Besides platinum+rhodium for NOx reduction and platinum+palladium for CO reduction, which catalyst can be used in catalytic converters?",
  "response": "In addition to platinum-rhodium and platinum-palladium, another catalyst that can be used in catalytic converters is **palladium-rhodium**. This combination can effectively facilitate reactions necessary for reducing harmful emissions. \n\nFurthermore, some newer catalytic converter technologies are exploring the use of **copper-based catalysts**, particularly in developing more efficient and cost-effective systems. Additionally, research is ongoing into transition metal oxides and other materials that can complement or replace traditional noble metals to enhance performance and reduce costs.\n\nIn hybrid setups, **ceramics and zeolite-based catalysts** are also being investigated for their potential in catalyzing reactions necessary for emissions reduction. \n\nLastly, it is worth mentioning that with advancements in technology, there is ongoing research into novel catalysts that may expand options beyond the conventional noble metal-based systems.",
